"Blowers P., Lownsbury J.M.","Carbon dioxide emission implications if hydrofluorocarbons are regulated: A refrigeration case study",2010,"Environmental Science and Technology","44","5",,"1526","1529",,,10.1021/es9023354,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77749264884&partnerID=40&md5=9d8c3ddd25499b9bcdaba12ea9ce460f","Department of Chemical and Environmental Engineering, University of Arizona, Tucson, AZ 85721-0011, United States","Blowers, P., Department of Chemical and Environmental Engineering, University of Arizona, Tucson, AZ 85721-0011, United States; Lownsbury, J.M., Department of Chemical and Environmental Engineering, University of Arizona, Tucson, AZ 85721-0011, United States","The U.S. is strongly considering regulating hydrofluorocarbons (HFCs) due to their global climate change forcing effects. Adrop-in replacement hydrofluoroether has been evaluated using a gate-to-grave life cycle assessment of greenhouse gas emissions for the trade-offs between direct and indirect carbon dioxide equivalent emissions compared to a current HFC and a historically used refrigerant. The results indicate current regulations being considered may increase global climate change. © 2010 American Chemical Society.",,"Carbon dioxide emissions; Current regulations; Global climate changes; Hydrofluorocarbons; Life-cycle assessments; Carbon dioxide; Global warming; Greenhouse gases; Inductively coupled plasma; Laws and legislation; Leakage (fluid); Life cycle; Gas emissions; carbon dioxide; fluorinated hydrocarbon; carbon dioxide; climate forcing; cooling; emission inventory; ether; global change; greenhouse gas; hydrofluorocarbon; life cycle analysis; pollution policy; regulatory framework; article; climate change; controlled study; environmental protection; freezing; global climate; greenhouse gas; life cycle assessment; United States; Carbon Dioxide; Chlorofluorocarbons; Chlorofluorocarbons, Methane; Climate Change; Environmental Pollutants; Hydrocarbons, Fluorin